    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Banners carried at the head of a procession, usually mounted upon a long staff or handle. They are usually rectangular, but may be triangular or of another shape. They are usually suspended at the top edge, but may be fixed on a stiff frame on all sides. They may be painted or richly embroidered; used in religious processions, royal processions, and for other occasions. They may carry the identification of a confraternity, congregation, or parish.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079245/Catholic Encyclopedia [online] (2003-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000049837/Thesaurus des Objets Religieux (1999)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Vaandels die men aan het hoofd van een processie draagt, gewoonlijk op een lange staf of steel. Doorgaans zijn ze rechthoekig, maar ze kunnen ook driehoekig zijn of een andere vorm hebben. Gewoonlijk zijn ze alleen aan de bovenkant bevestigd, maar soms zijn ze aan alle kanten vastgemaakt aan een stijf frame. Ze kunnen zijn beschilderd of zijn voorzien van rijk borduurwerk. Men gebruikt ze bij religieuze en koninklijke processies en andere gelegenheden.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Striscioni portati a capo di una processione, di solito montati su un lungo bastone o manico. Di solito sono rettangolari, ma possono essere triangolari o di altra forma. Di solito sono sospesi sul bordo superiore, ma possono essere fissati su un telaio rigido su tutti i lati. Possono essere dipinti o riccamente ricamati; usato in processioni religiose, processioni reali, e per altre occasioni. Possono portare l'identificazione di una confraternita, congregazione, o parrocchia.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Italian</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109543/Italian Term Processing (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>在遊行隊伍前端所執的旗幟，通常綁縛於長棍或把手上，大部分為長方形，但也可能為三角形或其他形狀，一般乃由頂端垂掛而下，但也可能各邊皆有硬框固定；旗幟上多半繪有圖樣或具精美刺繡，用於宗教與皇室遊行以及其他場合。旗幟上多半會帶有弟兄團，會眾或教區的標識。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
